 ethical and righteous, its entertainment value hinges upon suffering. Viewers can imagine themselves as deviant and ungovernable like the criminals in the show, thereby escaping a law-abiding lifestyle. Alternatively, they can identify with law enforcement officials, exercising violence, control, and "justice" on criminal others. Crimesploitation offers a sobering look at the depictions of criminals, policing, and punishment in modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCrime on television. 0aPunishment on television. 0aReality television programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTrue crime television programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh  aCrime.  aCultural Criminology.  aCultural History.  aLaw & Society.  aMass Incarceration.  aMedia Studies.  aNeoliberalism.  aPunishment.  aReality Television.  apopular culture.1 aKaplan, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363174840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631748423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631748/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles